<h2>What this is</h2>
<p>You will pick one of <strong>8 water-rights disputes</strong>. Within that case, you'll pick one <strong>stakeholder perspective</strong> (each case has 6-7 stakeholder options — farmer, government, industry, downstream community, NGO, etc.). You then produce a <strong>Stakeholders Map</strong> (a visual representation of who's involved, what they want, and how they relate) plus a <strong>Position Paper</strong> (2 pages or 4-min video) advocating for your chosen stakeholder's position — <em>not your own default view</em>.</p>
<p>The defense is a <strong>multi-stakeholder Roundtable</strong> — peers representing competing stakeholders in the same case actively argue, propose, refuse, seek compromise. This is the fourth defense in the year-long arc and the first one with a real negotiation format (not Q&amp;A). The Roundtable does not need to reach consensus; real disputes often don't.</p>

<div class="callout warn">
  <div class="callout-title">📌 Trial-aware: three pedagogical arms</div>
  <p>Unit 5 is Matthew's trial unit. Three sections, three slightly different scaffolds, same skill being built:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Section A (BoodleBox arm)</strong>: students <em>build</em> their own Stakeholder Voice AI bot for their chosen stakeholder — the <strong>Boodle Build Assignment</strong>. Building the bot is the deepest way to learn the perspective.</li>
    <li><strong>Section B (Flint guided-tutor arm)</strong>: students work with pre-built Flint Stakeholder Voice tutors. Linear scaffolding, consistent voice across stakeholders.</li>
    <li><strong>Section C (paper-based arm)</strong>: students work from paper-based Stakeholder Profile Packs (7 detailed profiles per case, no AI). Builds the same skill via close reading + interview-style preparation.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Each scaffold is designed to teach the same perspective-taking skill — pedagogically distinct, not quality-ranked. Your section's tools are introduced on Day 1.</p>
</div>

<h2>The 8 water-rights cases</h2>
<p>Pick one. The Cauvery is the local anchor; the other 7 are offered for distance + breadth. Each case includes 6-7 named stakeholders to choose from.</p>

