<h2>Required components</h2>
<ol>
  <li><strong>Stakeholders Map</strong> — visual representation (diagram, matrix, network map, infographic) + 1-page narrative walking a reader through who's involved, what each wants, where they conflict, where they might align. ≥5 specific stakeholders.</li>
  <li><strong>Position Paper</strong> — 2 pages written OR 4-min captioned video. Written from your chosen stakeholder's perspective, not your own. Voice must match the stakeholder (this is a T/T gate — see below).</li>
  <li><strong>AI Documentation Template</strong> — <em>required</em>, not optional. Documents your AI use (Hydrologist for case hydrology; Stakeholder Voice for perspective-taking; any other AI). Section A students document the Boodle Build process separately.</li>
  <li><strong>Stakeholder Roundtable participation</strong> — 2-min opening statement + ≥3 substantive responses to other stakeholders + at least 1 negotiation move (proposing trade, conceding a point, asking a substantive clarifying question).</li>
</ol>

<h2>What you'll be scored on</h2>
<p>U5 introduces <strong>perspective-taking as the year's T/T centerpiece</strong>. K/U covers water-system + water-rights knowledge. T/T covers whether you genuinely argued from the stakeholder's perspective (not your own). C covers clarity + Roundtable engagement + voice-match across formats.</p>
<p><strong>Grade weighting</strong>: Stakeholders Map + Position Paper 65% · Stakeholder Roundtable 20% · Formative work (Blocks 1-4 activities, OPVL practice, stakeholder mapping, peer feedback) 15%.</p>

<div class="callout warn">
  <div class="callout-title">📌 Four scoring gates worth naming up front</div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Voice-match is a T/T gate.</strong> If your Position Paper reads as your own view in slightly different words (same arguments + evidence you'd personally cite), T/T caps at 3-4. The whole assessment is built around perspective-taking; if you didn't take the perspective, T/T reflects that.</li>
    <li><strong>Stakeholder specificity is a K/U gate.</strong> If your Stakeholders Map names generic groups ("farmers," "government," "environmentalists") instead of specific identifiable stakeholders, K/U caps at 5-6. Real stakeholder analysis names specific groups — "Tamil Nadu Cauvery delta farmers (5th-gen rice growers)" not "farmers."</li>
    <li><strong>AI Documentation is a K/U gate.</strong> Same as prior units. If AI used and Template missing or trivial, K/U caps at 3-4.</li>
    <li><strong>Negotiation move is a C signal.</strong> Strong Paper + mere restatement in Roundtable (no real negotiation move) caps C at 5-6. The Roundtable is negotiation, not Q&amp;A.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<h2>AI Documentation</h2>
<p>Required regardless of which arm you're in. If you use the <a href="/ai-partners/the-hydrologist/">Hydrologist</a>, <a href="/ai-partners/stakeholder-voice/">Stakeholder Voice</a>, <a href="/ai-partners/the-source-evaluator/">Source Evaluator</a>, <a href="/ai-partners/the-skeptic/">Skeptic</a>, or any other AI tool, the <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation Template</a> is required. Section A students additionally document the Boodle Build process — what design choices you made when constructing your stakeholder's bot, which felt right, which the bot got wrong when tested with peers.</p>

